    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "c1e0702e-ee51-4839-9663-4b551858ed4e",
        "score": 0.4948529,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. discusses the utilization of different status types for market resources and their impact on market operations.\n\n**Status Type Utilization:**\n- Market Participants can modify resource control parameters by selecting a status type in their resource plans, which dictates how the resource functions.\n- In 2010, there were five status types: available, unavailable, self-scheduled, manual, and supplemental.\n- In late February 2011, the \"manual\" status was discontinued and replaced with several new types: exigent conditions, intermittent, qualifying facility, quick start, shut down, start up, and testing.\n- Only the \"available\" status allows full market utilization of a resource, enabling it to adjust output and set system prices.\n- \"Manual\" status indicates uncontrollable resources that cannot set prices and are dispatched at their last known output.\n- Self-scheduled resources operate based on predetermined output levels regardless of market conditions.\n- \"Unavailable\" status means the resource is offline and not usable by the market or participant.\n- \"Supplemental\" status means the resource is offline but can come online within ten minutes.\n- Available status units are most valuable to the market as they can respond quickly to instructions, helping resolve congestion and operational constraints.\n\n**Generation by Status Type:**\n- Most generation comes from market-available resources, allowing efficient operation and resolution of constraints.\n- The \"Start-up, Shut-down, and Test\" category was introduced in February 2011.\n- Intermittent resources are gaining importance in the EIS Market, with status types separated to categorize generation properly.\n- There is a noted steady decline in self-dispatched generation.\n\nOverall, the page explains how different resource status types affect market participation, resource dispatch, and generation efficiency, highlighting changes made in 2011 to improve categorization and market operation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2011/page_65.jpg",
          "page_num": 65,
          "title": "2011 State of the Market",
          "year": 2011,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7c0f1a1e-574d-4334-af58-b7129ce5496d",
        "score": 0.47597218,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit discusses two main topics related to unit commitment and dispatch processes:\n\n1. **Ramp Products Design Recommendations:**\n   - The document highlights the importance of designing ramp products that reflect true system conditions and incentivize flexibility.\n   - It references other RTO/ISO markets like Midcontinent ISO, California ISO, and ISO New England, which have implemented or are developing ramp products.\n   - Recommended features for ramp product design include:\n     - Two separate products for ramp capability up and ramp capability down.\n     - Co-optimization with energy and other products to ensure the most economical solution.\n     - Pricing based on opportunity cost.\n     - No restrictions on resource type, as long as the resource can reliably provide the required ramp.\n     - Consideration of both expected and unexpected ramping needs.\n\n2. **Virtual Trading (Section 3.4):**\n   - Market participants in SPP\u2019s Integrated Marketplace can submit virtual energy offers and bids in the day-ahead market at any settlement location.\n   - Virtual offers (increment offers) represent energy sales in the day-ahead market that must be bought back in real-time, similar to generation.\n   - Virtual bids (decrement bids) represent energy purchases in the day-ahead market that must be sold back in real-time, similar to load.\n   - The purpose of virtual trading is to help converge day-ahead and real-time market prices and improve day-ahead unit commitment decisions.\n   - For effective price convergence, virtual trading requires sufficient competition, transparency in the day-ahead market, reliable unit commitment, real-time market operating practices, and predictability of market events.\n   - Since the market's inception in 2014, virtual participation has been moderate but increasing.\n\nThe page ends with a reference to Figure 3-22, which presumably provides additional data or illustration related to virtual trading.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2017/page_91.jpg",
          "page_num": 91,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "abaade85-205c-4288-b084-bdd82c69aa46",
        "score": 0.47484943,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report discusses two main topics related to power market transactions and market-to-market processes.\n\n1. **Fixed and Dispatchable Transactions:**\n   - The average monthly dispatchable transactions increased from 80 MW in 2020 to 100 MW in 2021.\n   - The highest dispatchable transactions occurred in November, peaking at nearly 200 MW.\n   - Up-to-TUC transactions were limited to February and March, averaging 24 MW each month.\n   - Fixed transactions dominate interchange transactions due to factors such as bilateral contracts with external entities, Southwestern Power Administration hydro contracts, and generally lower prices in the SPP market compared to other RTOs.\n   - To improve market efficiency, participants are encouraged to use dispatchable and up-to-TUC imports and exports more, as these allow setting a specific strike price, enabling more economic imports and exports.\n\n2. **Market-to-Market (M2M) Process:**\n   - SPP started the M2M process with MISO in March 2015, fulfilling a FERC requirement that also included regulation compensation and long-term congestion rights.\n   - Each Regional Transmission Organization (RTO) is allocated property rights on market-to-market constraints, called firm flow entitlements (FFE).\n   - Each RTO calculates its real-time usage (market flow) and exchanges money (market-to-market settlements) for redispatch based on the difference between market flow and firm flow entitlement.\n   - The non-monitoring RTO receives money from the monitoring RTO if its market flow is below its firm flow entitlement and pays if above.\n   - Figure 2-44 (not shown) illustrates monthly payments between SPP and MISO, where positive values indicate payments from MISO to SPP, and negative values indicate payments from SPP to MISO.\n\nFootnotes clarify that the M2M process and related mechanisms were implemented one year after the SPP Integrated Marketplace go-live, allowing efficient management of constraints by exchanging information and using the more economic redispatch. The monitoring RTO typically manages the limiting constraint and has the most impact and resources for relieving congestion.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_82.jpg",
          "page_num": 82,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "bdf08a0c-3b7f-489c-8939-ea811e351481",
        "score": 0.4662248,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report discusses the Integrated Marketplace operated by SPP, a Regional Transmission Organization (RTO) authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC). SPP was granted RTO status in 2004 and provides various services to its members, including reliability coordination, tariff administration, regional scheduling, reserve sharing, transmission expansion planning, wholesale electricity market operations, and training. The report focuses on the 2019 calendar year of the SPP wholesale electricity market, known as the Integrated Marketplace, which began on March 1, 2014.\n\nThe Integrated Marketplace features a full day-ahead market with transmission congestion rights, virtual trading, a reliability unit commitment process, a real-time balancing market, and a price-based operating reserves market. A key aspect of the marketplace is the implementation of a single balancing authority. The primary benefit of the day-ahead market is improved efficiency in daily resource commitments, along with joint optimization of available capacity for energy and operating reserves.\n\nThe section also describes the SPP market footprint, which is located in the westernmost part of the Eastern Interconnection. It borders the Midcontinent ISO (MISO) to the east, the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) to the south, and the Western Interconnection to the west. The document references a figure showing the operating regions of nine RTO/ISO markets in the U.S. and Canada, along with a detailed view of the SPP footprint. Additionally, SPP has connections with non-RTO/ISO areas such as Saskatchewan Power Corporation, Associated Electric Cooperative, and Southwestern Power Administration. A footnote clarifies that Southwestern Power Administration belongs to the SPP RTO, Reliability Coordinator, and Reserve Sharing Group footprints, while Associated Electric Cooperative belongs to the SPP Reserve Sharing Group.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2019/page_36.jpg",
          "page_num": 36,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET 2019",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "241cfaaf-910a-4d5a-a3fc-19ec05405108",
        "score": 0.46429807,
        "text": "This document page from Southwest Power Pool, Inc.'s Market Monitoring Unit discusses the unit commitment and dispatch process within the Integrated Marketplace, focusing on the commitment process.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- SPP implemented a ramp capability product on March 1, 2022.\n- There has been a shift in the average percent of total offered capacity by commitment status, with a 5 percentage point decrease in self-commit status and a 5 percentage point increase in market status.\n\nSection 3.1 Commitment Process explains that the Integrated Marketplace uses centralized unit commitment to efficiently schedule and dispatch generation resources to meet energy demand and operating reserve requirements. Most commitments start in the day-ahead market, which aims to commit enough capacity to meet the loads bid into that market. However, due to differences between day-ahead and real-time conditions and locational issues, additional capacity often needs to be committed outside the day-ahead market.\n\nThis additional commitment is managed through reliability unit commitment (RUC) processes and manual commitments. SPP employs five reliability commitment processes:\n\n1. Multi-day reliability assessment (MDRA)\n2. Day-ahead reliability unit commitment (DA RUC) process\n3. Intra-day reliability unit commitment (ID RUC) process\n4. Short-term intra-day reliability unit commitment (ST RUC) process\n5. Manual commitment instructions issued by the Regional Transmission Organization (RTO)\n\nThe page also includes a timeline figure (Figure 3-1) illustrating when these various commitment processes occur relative to the operating day, showing the sequence from multi-day reliability assessment through day-ahead market and RUC processes to intra-day and manual commitments.\n\nA footnote references the tariff revisions related to the ramp capability product (FERC Docket No. ER20-1617).",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_104.jpg",
          "page_num": 104,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

